Adrenal glands
Adrenal glands are small, yellow glands located on top of each kidney, part of the endocrine system that produce hormones.

Adrenocortical carcinoma
Adrenocortical carcinoma is a rare type of adrenal gland cancer that begins in the adrenal cortex.

Chapter 3: Types of treatment
Chapter 3 of the book covers the types of treatment available for cancer patients.

Basal Cell Skin Cancer
Basal cell skin cancer is a type of skin cancer that can return to the area where it was originally found or metastasize to lymph nodes or distant parts of the body.<SEP>Basal cell skin cancer is the most common type of skin cancer, diagnosed in about 3 million cases annually in the United States, and is typically curable when detected early.

Questions to ask
A section in each chapter of the book that provides suggested questions to help patients understand their care.

Adrenal tumors
Adrenal tumors can occur in one or both adrenal glands and are categorized as benign, functional, or malignant.

NCCN Guidelines for Patients
The NCCN Guidelines for Patients are trusted by patients and providers; they clearly explain current care recommendations made by respected experts in the field, based on the latest research and practices at leading cancer centers.<SEP>A patient-focused document published by the National Comprehensive Cancer Network that provides guidance on cancer care and family health history.<SEP>A set of guidelines provided by the National Comprehensive Cancer Network for patients with skin cancer.

data.entity_name: Chapter 4: Treatment by risk and recurrence
data.content:
Chapter 4: Treatment by risk and recurrence
Chapter 4 of the book focuses on how treatment is tailored based on the risk level and recurrence of cancer.

Neuroblastoma
Neuroblastoma is a rare type of adrenal tumor that affects children under 5 years of age and can spread.<SEP>Neuroblastoma is a rare type of adrenal tumor that is cancerous, affecting children under 5, and can spread to bones and other parts of the body.

Cushing syndrome
Cushing syndrome is a condition caused by an adrenal tumor producing excess cortisol.

data.entity_name: Testing for basal cell skin cancer
data.content:
Testing for basal cell skin cancer
Testing for basal cell skin cancer involves medical history, physical exam, skin exam, biopsy, and imaging studies to diagnose the condition.

Recurrence
Recurrence in cancer refers to when the cancer returns to the area where it was originally found or has metastasized to lymph nodes or distant parts of the body.

Biopsy
Biopsy is a medical procedure to remove a small sample of tissue for examination to diagnose cancer.

Imaging
Imaging refers to medical tests such as CT or MRI scans that visualize internal structures.

Medical Binder
A physical notebook or binder used to organize medical records, including test results, insurance cards, and other health documents.

Blood Test Results
Results from blood tests that are used to monitor health conditions and detect diseases.

Imaging Results
Results from imaging tests (such as X-rays, CT, MRI) that provide visual images of the body's internal structures.

Cancer Reports
Reports related to specific types of cancer, including diagnosis and treatment details.

Family History
Information about the health conditions and diseases that run in a family, including genetic predispositions.

Medical History
A record of a person's health issues, treatments, and medical conditions throughout their life.

Second Medical Opinion
A consultation with a second healthcare provider to review a patient's condition and treatment plan.

Physical Examination
A comprehensive health assessment by a healthcare provider that includes checking vital signs and physical symptoms.

CT Scan
A computed tomography scan that uses X-rays and computer technology to create detailed 3D images of the body.

MRI Scan
A magnetic resonance imaging scan that uses radio waves and magnets to produce detailed images of the body without X-rays.

PET Scan
A positron emission tomography scan that uses a radioactive tracer to detect cancer cells and other abnormalities.

FDG-PET/CT Scan
A combined scan that uses a PET scan with a CT scan to provide detailed images of cancer cells and their spread.

Adrenal Tumors
Tumors that develop in the adrenal glands, which can be associated with various health conditions including cancer.<SEP>Adrenal tumors are growths that can occur in the adrenal glands, and most are noncancerous (benign), but some can be cancerous.

Family Health History
The medical history of blood relatives that helps identify genetic conditions and diseases.

Prednisone
A corticosteroid medication used to reduce inflammation and treat various autoimmune conditions.

Diphenhydramine
An over-the-counter antihistamine medication (sold under the brand name Benadryl) used to treat allergies and as a sleep aid.

Contrast
A substance used in medical imaging to enhance the visibility of internal structures, administered orally or intravenously, and may cause allergic reactions.

FDG-PET
A type of PET scan that uses 18-Fluorodeoxyglucose as a tracer to detect cancer cells by their increased glucose metabolism.

SSTRPET
A type of PET scan that uses somatostatin receptors to target tumors, particularly useful in adrenal tumors.

18-Fluorodeoxyglucose
A radioactive sugar compound used as a tracer in FDG-PET scans to detect cancer cells by their increased metabolic activity.

Radiologist
A medical professional who interprets medical images and reports on test results.

Tracer
A radioactive substance injected into the vein to help locate cancer cells in PET scans.

Allergic Reaction
A reaction to a substance that causes an immune system response, which can be life-threatening and requires medical attention.

Epidermis
The top layer of skin that provides a waterproof barrier and creates skin color (melanin).

Dermis
The middle layer of skin that contains connective tissue, blood vessels, oil and sweat glands, nerves, and hair follicles.

United States
The country where about 3 million cases of basal cell skin cancer are diagnosed each year.

Squamous cells
Flat cells found in the upper part of the epidermis that form the outer layer of skin.

Hypodermis
The deepest layer of skin composed of fat and connective tissue.

Basal cells
Cells found in the lower part of the epidermis that constantly divide to form new skin cells.

Melanocytes
Cells in the lower part of the epidermis that produce melanin, responsible for skin, hair, and eye color.

Melanin
A pigment that gives color to skin, hair, and eyes and protects against harmful ultraviolet (UV) rays.

Tanning beds
Devices that emit UV radiation for tanning, which can increase the risk of skin cancer.

data.entity_name: NCCN Patient Guides for Cancer app
data.content:
NCCN Patient Guides for Cancer app
A mobile application developed by the National Comprehensive Cancer Network that provides patient guides for cancer.

Basal Cell Skin Cancer Book
A book that focuses exclusively on basal cell skin cancer, including information on diagnosis, treatment, and prevention.

National Comprehensive Cancer Network
A non-profit organization that provides evidence-based guidelines for cancer care.

Sun
The celestial body that emits UV radiation which can cause skin cancer.

Skin lesions
Abnormal skin growths that can be a sign of basal cell skin cancer, including flat, pale areas, red patches, bumps, or open sores.

Adrenal Cancer
Adrenal cancer is a rare cancer that starts in one or both of the adrenal glands, affecting children under 5 and adults in their 40s and 50s, and can be cured if caught early.

UV radiation
Radiation from the sun or artificial sources that can damage skin cells and lead to skin cancer.

Pheochromocytoma
Pheochromocytoma is a tumor that begins in the adrenal medulla, characterized by symptoms of high blood pressure, headache, rapid heartbeat, and sweating, and can be benign or cancerous.

Adrenocortical Carcinoma
Adrenocortical carcinoma (ACC) is a type of adrenal cancer that starts in the adrenal cortex, occurring in children under 5 and adults in their 40s and 50s, and can be cured if detected early.

Adenoma
Adenoma is the most common type of adrenal tumor, noncancerous, and can be functioning or nonfunctioning, and may not require treatment if small and not causing symptoms.

Adrenal Glands
Adrenal glands are small, yellow glands that are part of the endocrine system and produce hormones.

Endocrine System
The endocrine system is a network of tissues and organs that produce hormones to regulate body functions.

Hormones
Hormones are chemical substances produced by glands that travel through the bloodstream to control body functions.

Beckwith-Wiedemann Syndrome
Beckwith-Wiedemann syndrome is a hereditary condition that increases the risk of developing adrenal tumors.

Familial Adenomatous Polyposis (FAP)
Familial adenomatous polyposis (FAP) is a hereditary condition that increases the risk of adrenal tumors.

Carney Complex
Carney complex is a hereditary condition that increases the risk of adrenal tumors.

Li-Fraumeni Syndrome
Li-Fraumeni syndrome is a hereditary condition that increases the risk of adrenal tumors.

Hereditary Paragangliomapheochromocytoma (PGL/PCC) Syndrome
Hereditary paragangliomapheochromocytoma (PGL/PCC) syndrome is a hereditary condition that increases the risk of adrenal tumors.

Lynch Syndrome
Lynch syndrome is a hereditary condition that increases the risk of adrenal tumors.

Multiple Endocrine Neoplasia Type 1 (MEN 1)
Multiple endocrine neoplasia type 1 (MEN 1) is a hereditary condition that increases the risk of adrenal tumors.

Neurofibromatosis Type 1 (NF1)
Neurofibromatosis type 1 (NF1) is a hereditary condition that increases the risk of adrenal tumors.

Multiple Endocrine Neoplasia Type 2 (MEN 2)
Multiple endocrine neoplasia type 2 (MEN 2) is a hereditary condition that increases the risk of adrenal tumors.

NCCN
NCCN (National Comprehensive Cancer Network) is an organization that provides guidelines for cancer patients.

Von Hippel-Lindau Syndrome (VHL)
Von Hippel-Lindau syndrome (VHL) is a hereditary condition that increases the risk of adrenal tumors.
